│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe verifier reports “Instruction does not dominate │
│ all uses!” for an insertelement used by a newly created shufflevector. This   │
│ implies the pass is emitting a shuffle before the definition of one of its    │
│ operands, violating SSA dominance.\n\nThe minimized IR triggers SLP’s path    │
│ that collects insertelement chains and emits a final shuffle to replace and   │
│ rebuild the chain (the ‘ShuffledInserts’ handling). In this path, SLP         │
│ currently sets the IRBuilder insertion point to the last insertelement in the │
│ chain (LastInsert) and then creates the shuffle using operands taken from the │
│ buildvector chain. Under certain circumstances, one of those operands (an     │
│ insertelement) is defined after this insertion point, making the shuffle use  │
│ a value that does not yet dominate it.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:\n- The    │
│ first transformation leading to the broken IR is inside SLP, not the verifier │
│ itself. The verifier is simply catching the dominance break.\n- The crash     │
│ message shows a freshly created insertelement (%4) and a shufflevector (%2)   │
│ using it, with %4 not dominating %2. This matches the ShuffledInserts flow    │
│ where we create a shuffle and then rebuild/erase insertelements.\n- In        │
│ SLPVectorizer.cpp, around lines 18976–19040, SLP sorts insertelements, sets   │
│ Builder.SetInsertPoint(LastInsert), and calls performExtractsShuffleAction to │
│ create the new shuffle using FirstInsert->getOperand(0) and masks, then       │
│ rewires and erases the insertelements.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe        │
│ insertion point selection is incorrect for the newly created shuffle:         │
│ Builder.SetInsertPoint(LastInsert) does not guarantee that all operands       │
│ passed to CreateShuffle dominate this location. The lambda passed to          │
│ performExtractsShuffleAction chooses operands like FirstInsert->getOperand(0) │
│ and potentially other discovered values; these may be later-inserted          │
│ insertelements (or derived through analysis) that end up defined after        │
│ LastInsert due to prior transformations or the subsequent “rebuild            │
│ buildvector chain” logic that moves instructions. As a result, the shuffle    │
│ can be placed before a defining insertelement (%4), violating                 │
│ dominance.\n\nWe need to place the shuffle after its operands’ definitions. A │
│ simple and robust fix is to set the builder insertion point relative to the   │
│ earliest operand we know we’ll use: FirstInsert->getOperand(0). If that       │
│ operand is an instruction, we can set the insertion point to just after it    │
│ (or after its next non-debug instruction), ensuring it dominates the shuffle. │
│ If it’s not an instruction, we can keep the current strategy.\n\n4. Proposed  │
│ Edit Point(s)\n- File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n-     │
│ Location: Around the code that sets the insertion point before creating the   │
│ final shuffle for ShuffledInserts (currently at line ~18982).\n- Change:      │
│ Instead of unconditional Builder.SetInsertPoint(LastInsert), compute the      │
│ primary operand (FirstInsert->getOperand(0)), and if it is an Instruction,    │
│ set the insertion point after that instruction. Otherwise, fall back to the   │
│ old LastInsert position.\n\nConcrete edit (lines 18982–18987):\n\nReplace:\n  │
│ Builder.SetInsertPoint(LastInsert);\n  auto Vector =                          │
│ ShuffledInserts[I].ValueMasks.takeVector();\n  Value *NewInst =               │
│ performExtractsShuffleAction<Value>(\n      MutableArrayRef(Vector.data(),    │
│ Vector.size()),\n      FirstInsert->getOperand(0),\n      [](Value *Vec)      │
│ {\n\nWith:\n  // Ensure the shuffle is inserted after its primary operand to  │
│ satisfy dominance.\n  if (auto *BaseOpI =                                     │
│ dyn_cast<Instruction>(FirstInsert->getOperand(0))) {\n                        │
│ Builder.SetInsertPoint(BaseOpI->getNextNonDebugInstruction());\n  } else {\n  │
│ Builder.SetInsertPoint(LastInsert);\n  }\n  auto Vector =                     │
│ ShuffledInserts[I].ValueMasks.takeVector();\n  Value *NewInst =               │
│ performExtractsShuffleAction<Value>(\n      MutableArrayRef(Vector.data(),    │
│ Vector.size()),\n      FirstInsert->getOperand(0),\n      [](Value *Vec)      │
│ {\n\nThis ensures the newly created shuffle is emitted after its base operand │
│ definition and before rebuilding/erasing the insertelement chain, thereby     │
│ maintaining correct SSA dominance.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy adjusting the        │
│ insertion point for the final shuffle to be after the base operand’s          │
